On your own:

Load present day data: 

source("http://www.openintro.org/stat/data/present.R")

1: There are 63 years and 3 variables in the data set. The years go from 1940 - 2002, and the three variables are: year, boys, girls.

dim(present)
## [1] 63  3
names(present)
## [1] "year"  "boys"  "girls"

2: The present birth records in the United States are drastically higher than Dr. Arbuthnot’s baptism records. Present day births over time range from about 2.5 million - 4.5 million per year where as Dr. Arbuthnot’s data showed a birth rate of about 10,000 - 16,125. The boy to girl ratio from Dr. Arbuthnot’s data is slightly higher than present day data.

present <- present %>%
  mutate(total = boys + girls)
qplot(x = year, y = total, data = present, geom = "line")

3: The overall boy to girl ratio from Dr. Arbuthnot’s data is higher than the present day boy to girl ratio. The present day boy to girl ratio has been slowly decreasing, but is still slightly above 1, which means that more boys than girls are born every year. This supports Dr. Arbuthnot’s obeservation that boys are born in greater proportion than girls.

present <- present %>%
  mutate(boy_to_girl_ratio = boys / girls)
qplot(x = year, y = boy_to_girl_ratio , data = present, geom = "line")

4: 1961 had the greatest total number of births with 4,268,326 children born.

present <- present %>%
  mutate(total = boys + girls)
